\f1\b\fs36 \cf0 \strokec2 What I'm proposing\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf0 Bug fix \'97 5 minutes of work\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Two different counts exist in the data:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 485 watches
\f0\b0  = every individual record (e.g., Submariner 126610LN with 3235 Clone movement is one record; Submariner 126610LN with 2836 Asian movement is another).\
\ls1\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 83 model families
\f0\b0  = unique brand + family pairs (all Submariner records collapse into 1 family).\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 The "All" chip was wired to show families (83). The per-brand chips (
\f2\fs26 ROLEX 108
\f0\fs24 ) show watch counts. That inconsistency is the bug.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 Fix:
\f0\b0  make "All" show 
\f2\fs26 485
\f0\fs24  so it matches the rest. Add a small one-line caption above the cards that says 
\f2\fs26 // SHOWING 83 FAMILIES
\f0\fs24  so you understand why fewer cards appear than the chip number \'97 the cards on the browse view are families, not individual watches.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs28 \cf0 Deep-links \'97 the honest version\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\b0\fs24 \cf0 Here's the tradeoff you need to understand before I commit to an approach:\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf0 There is no clean way to deep-link to "the exact watch" on every dealer's site automatically.
\f0\b0  Dealers don't have APIs. Each runs their own catalog on WordPress, OpenCart, Shopify, or custom code. To get a 100% exact "/product/sub-126610ln/" URL for every (watch \'d7 dealer) combination would require either:\
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf0 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 (A) Web-scraping every dealer's catalog.
\f0\b0  Fragile, Cloudflare-blocked, breaks every time a dealer changes a URL. Not honest engineering.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 (B) Hand-curating 33 dealers \'d7 485 watches = ~16,000 URLs.
\f0\b0  Not realistic.\
\ls2\ilvl0
\f1\b \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 (C) Using each dealer's built-in search.
\f0\b0  For most dealers, you can construct a URL like 
\f2\fs26 https://jtime.io/?s=126610LN
\f0\fs24  that runs a search on their site for the watch's reference number. The user lands on a search results page showing matching products.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0
\cf0 My plan = 
\f1\b (C) by default + (B) as an opt-in for watches you really care about
\f0\b0 .\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

